Eclipse watchers flocked to Hawaii and Mexico in anticipation for the
July 11 solar eclipse.  The Baja area of Mexico will get the largest
influx because of its easy access from the US and since the eclipse
duration will last longest there.  Mexico's government has formed an
Intersecretarial Commission to oversee production of protective
viewing lenses.  Sun-worshiping Aztecs in ancient times viewed
eclipses as bad omens.  A futuristic escape from eclipse threats was
proposed by "Angel" of the Intergalactic Guardian Command who
advocates taking spaceships to the fourth dimension.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d08"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06193235"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="F">     

The San Jose Mercury News was providing readers with information
concerning timing of the coming solar eclipse and viewing hints and
warnings.  In the Bay area the eclipse will peak at 10:20 AM and last
for 24 minutes but only about half of the sun's diameter will be
blocked.  No one should look directly at the sun even with ordinary or
makeshift sunglasses.  Viewers should look at the shadows or punch a
hole in a piece of paper and look down at the shadow.  Without
precautions, serious eye damage can occur.</SUM>

