TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP901231-0012"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="F">     

Mexico is forming elaborate plans months in advance of the "solar
eclipse of the century" which will occur on July 11.  The 165 mile
wide path extends from Hawaii, across Mexico to Brazil and the area
will go dark for almost seven minutes, the maximum length of time for
a total solar eclipse.  The Latin American rainy season may hamper
viewing.  Eclipse 1991, a Mexican government commission, expects a
huge financial gain for the country.  Tourist facilities are heavily
booked and expected to reach capacity.  Ships are being prepared to
serve as floating hotels and viewing platforms.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d08"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06161012"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="F">  

Airline reservations, rental cars, and hotel rooms in prime viewing
areas for the coming solar eclipse are nearly impossible to get.
Hawaii and Mexico's Baja are the most favored areas because of usually
clear skies.  Hawaii may be the glamor viewing area, but crowds will
be greatest in Baja.  The eclipse will last longest, nearly seven
minutes, in the town of Tuxpan on Mexico's west coast.  Mexican
authorities, concerned about overloading of accommodations and
facilities will have a checkpoint at Guerrero Negro, halfway down the
peninsula and turn back travelers without evidence of
accommodations.</SUM>

<SUM
